[Ted Chiang](!Wikipedia) is an American SF author of short stories & a novella, noted for both the high quality and fewness of his writings.
Most are collected in his 2002 anthology _[Stories of Your Life and Others](!Wikipedia)_ ([my review](https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/369923171)).

Chiang's stories can be described as rigorous world-building[^interview], taking seriously premises such as the Kabbalah (["72 Letters"](https://web.archive.org/web/20010802144026/http://www.tor.com/72ltrs.html)) or intelligence enhancement (["Understand"](https://web.archive.org/web/20140527121332/http://www.infinityplus.co.uk/stories/under.htm)) or self-consistent time loops (["The Merchant and the Alchemist's Gate"](https://pkubbs.net/attach/boards/ScienceFiction/M.1209705460.A/Ted_Chiang.pdf)) or a mechanical clockwork universe (["Exhalation"](http://www.nightshadebooks.com/Downloads/Exhalation%20-%20Ted%20Chiang.html)) or the problem of evil in a universe where God exists (["Hell Is the Absence of God"](http://www.ibooksonline.com/88/Text/hell.html)) and extending them logically, written in a lucid streamlined prose that (like Gene Wolfe's) seems simple & easy unless one has tried to write like that oneself, but (unlike, say, Greg Egan) use those worlds & concepts to examine and build up a powerful emotional point.
Each story has a unique starting point, and feels like a world or novel unto itself despite their short page counts.

